<subSubSection id="28FB6564FFD5D65B0AE4FEF310BD3795" pageId="3" pageNumber="694" type="breeding">
<paragraph id="605E36EFFFD5D65B0AE4FEF310BD3795" blockId="3.[172,1383,287,949]" pageId="3" pageNumber="694">
<emphasis id="5295EAFDFFD5D65B0AE4FEF3101B3725" bold="true" box="[174,308,287,316]" pageId="3" pageNumber="694">Breeding.</emphasis>
In New 
<collectingCountry id="18F6767FFFD5D65B0BFAFEF313383725" box="[432,535,287,316]" name="Guinea-Bissau" pageId="3" pageNumber="694">Guinea</collectingCountry>
, ten female Large Long-fingered Bats captured in July were reproductively inactive, but six females captured in mid-August each carried one halfdeveloped fetus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="28FB6564FFD5D65B0AE7FE79154D3431" pageId="3" pageNumber="694" type="activity">
<paragraph id="605E36EFFFD5D65B0AE7FE79154D3431" blockId="3.[172,1383,287,949]" pageId="3" pageNumber="694">
<emphasis id="5295EAFDFFD5D65B0AE7FE7910B737AB" bold="true" box="[173,408,405,434]" pageId="3" pageNumber="694">Activity patterns.</emphasis>
The Large Long-fingered Bat is thought to be mainly nocturnal. It is cave dwelling. Echolocation calls have downward FM signals. Mean call characteristics in 
<collectingCountry id="18F6767FFFD5D65B0A9DFE3310783419" box="[215,343,479,512]" name="Thailand" pageId="3" pageNumber="694">Thailand</collectingCountry>
are start frequency 85-3 kHz, end frequency 42-3 kHz, peak frequency 47-4 kHz, duration 4-3 milliseconds, and interval 65-2 milliseconds.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="28FB6564FFD5D65B0AE5FDC2108F34DE" pageId="3" pageNumber="694" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="605E36EFFFD5D65B0AE5FDC2108F34DE" blockId="3.[172,1383,287,949]" pageId="3" pageNumber="694">
<emphasis id="5295EAFDFFD5D65B0AE5FDC212463456" bold="true" box="[175,873,558,591]" pageId="3" pageNumber="694">Movements, Home range and Social organization.</emphasis>
Colonies in caves usually have a few hundred individuals but can reach up to several thousand. Large Long-fingered Bats usually share roosts with other cave-dwelling bats (Taphozous, Hipposideros, Rhinolophus, 
<taxonomicName id="A7E14D6CFFD5D65B0AFBFD46106334DE" authorityName="Bonaparte" authorityYear="1837" box="[177,332,682,711]" class="Mammalia" family="Miniopteridae" genus="Miniopterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="694" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Miniopterus</taxonomicName>
, etc.).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="28FB6564FFD5D65B0AE5FD2015E534F4" box="[175,1226,716,749]" pageId="3" pageNumber="694" type="conservation">
<paragraph id="605E36EFFFD5D65B0AE5FD2015E534F4" blockId="3.[172,1383,287,949]" box="[175,1226,716,749]" pageId="3" pageNumber="694">
<emphasis id="5295EAFDFFD5D65B0AE5FD20132234F4" bold="true" box="[175,525,716,749]" pageId="3" pageNumber="694">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
Classified as Least Concern on The IUCN Red List.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
